            "file": "Hermanubis.docx",
            "text": "Hermanubis: A Syncretic Deity of Ancient Egypt\n\nHermanubis is a Graeco-Egyptian god resulting from the combination of Hermes from Greek mythology and Anubis from Egyptian mythology. It is believed that the assimilation of the two gods led to the emergence of Hermanubis iconography. In Roman Alexandria, a new depiction of Anubis emerged with Greek attributes, often represented as an anthropomorphic young god flanked by a dog, holding the same attributes as Anubis. However, no inscription directly identifies this representation as Hermanubis.\n\nOne of the unique aspects of Hermanubis is its formation as a polytheophoric name, combining the names of two deities. However, it is distinguished from other polytheophoric names because it refers to a specific deity that has been independently attested in Roman Egypt. Most of the names based on Hermanubis are found in papyri dating from the second and third centuries AD, disappearing from evidence after the fourth century. This chronological distribution matches the iconographical representations of the fully anthropomorphic god known as \"Hermanubis,\" which can be found on coins and statues from the second or third century AD.\n\nThe majority of individuals with the name Hermanubis are from Alexandria or the Cynopolite nome. Alexandria was the main cult center for the fully anthropomorphic Hermanubis, with archaeological evidence such as a dedication and a statuette found in the Serapeum precinct. The Cynopolite nome's connection to Hermanubis is more suggested by onomastic evidence, with one of the individuals named after him likely being a priest of Anubis and associated gods in the Cynopolite village of Laura. Some Alexandrian coins also depict the Cynopolite nome with an anthropomorphic Hermanubis on their reverse.\n\nFrom the onomastic survey, it can be concluded that: 1) Names based on Hermanubis are different from other polytheophoric names in Roman Egypt because they refer to a specific and independently attested god, 2) The onomastic evidence overlaps with the representations of the anthropomorphic Alexandrian god known as \"Hermanubis,\" supporting his designation as such, and 3) Hermanubis is closely associated with the traditional Anubis and should not be separated too forcefully from him.\n\nThe name Hermanubis is also found outside of Egypt in an inscription from Dion in Macedonia, and the form of the name is different from the one used in Egypt. This suggests that the cult of Hermanubis was popular outside of its original home in the Roman period, as evidenced by a dedication in Thessalonike and a statue from the Sarapeum of Carthage.\n"
